Tajik music closely related other Central Asian forms music The classical music shashmaqam which Uzbeks also developed classical music Tajiksclarification needed and made their distinctive own Southern Tajikistan has distinctive form folk music called falak which played celebrations for weddings circumcisions and other occasions Tajik folk music traditionally divided into three styles Pamir MountainBadakhshan province Central Kuhistoni Hisor Kulob Gharm provinces and Sogdianas northern style the latter part the same musical culture the adjacent regions Uzbekistan Kashkadarya Province and Surkhandarya Province There are many kinds songs both lyrical and instrument including work songs ceremonial funeral wedding and musical epics especially the central Tajik heroic legend Gurugli also known Omar Sham Sham Gharibi the song stranger early 20thcentury innovation poor farm laborers and other workers who had leave their land Gulgardoni springtime holiday also called Boychechak which includes carolling celebratory songs accompanied the dutar and doira Sayri Guli Lola the holiday tulips which includes accompanied choral and dance music The most important song this holiday called Naqshi Kalon The birth child cause for special musical celebration Traditional puppeteers play the doira qayroq surnay and nagora There are other variations and folk songs like Naat and Munojot performed the circumcision ceremony male child Traditional Tajik wedding music played sozanda professional musicians mostly female who are part ensembles called the dasta Badakhshan region inhabited Tajik Ismailis known for their sung spiritual poetry called madah Lutes are major part Ismaili folk music The Tajik anthem available YouTube 